December 8, 2016

Packages

library("tidyverse")

The tidyverse package loads a number of R packages that has recently been developed to support a clearner, more efficient and more coherent framework for data handling and data transformation in R.

Core tidyverse packages

Package Functionality
tibble Better data frames
dplyr Data manipulation
tidyr Data tidying
readr Data IO
purr Functional programming
ggplot2 Graphics

Reading data

traffic <- read_csv("../../BUinternet.txt")  ## Using the readr package
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  `machine name` = col_character(),
  timestamp = col_integer(),
  `user id` = col_integer(),
  url = col_character(),
  size = col_integer(),
  time = col_double()
)

This is a classical 1995 data set from Boston University on WWW data transfers.

Selecting

For tibbles, the intention is that the dplyr function select is used for variable selection instead of subsetting with [.

Summarizing by group

trafficSum <- arrange(
  summarize(
    group_by(traffic, `machine name`), 
    mSpeed = mean(speed), medSpeed = median(speed), 
    mSize = mean(size), medSize = median(size)
  ),
  medSize
)

A scatter plot

p <- ggplot(trafficSum, aes(x = medSize, y = medSpeed)) + 
  geom_point()  ## This geom constructs scatter plots
p  ## Evaluate p to get the figure drawn

Adding aesthetics

p <- p + aes(size = mSize)
p

Adding a regression line

p + geom_smooth(method = "lm",  ## Default is a scatter plot smoother
                show.legend = FALSE) + ## Don't mess up the legend
  xlab("Median size (byte)") + ylab("Median speed (byte / s)") +
  scale_size("Mean size (byte)")

The ggplot2 world

The ggplot2 package provides via the ggplot function (and qplot) a system for declarative specification of graphics.

  • Use aes to specify how variables are mapped to graphical aesthetics (x- and y-position, size, shape, color, fill)
  • Use geom_?? to specify the geometrical object (point, line, smooth, density, …)
  • Use stat_?? to specify a statistical transformation (sum, count, …).
  • Add different components of a plot via +.

Note that typical usage requires specification of a geometrical object, which will implicitly use a statistical transformation.

Using the larger traffic data

ggplot(traffic) +  ## Spec. of aesthetics postponed to geom
  geom_bar(aes(x = `machine name`)) +  ## Implicit usage of `stat_count`
  coord_flip() +  ## Convenient here
  scale_x_discrete(limits = trafficOrd$`machine name`)

Boxplots for each machine

ggplot(traffic) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = `machine name`, y = size)) + 
  coord_flip() + 
  scale_y_log10() + ## The distribution of size is heavy-tailed
  scale_x_discrete(limits = trafficSum$`machine name`)

A scatter plot using hexagonal binning

ggplot(traffic, aes(x = size, y = speed)) + 
  geom_hex() + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() + 
  geom_smooth()

Alternatives

The package dplyr provides a framework for data transformation – first of all based on the tibble data structure.

  • The base R functions with, within, transform, aggregate, subset, rbind, cbind and merge perform similar data transformations on data frames.
  • The dplyr package can work with SQL database backends. See the Databases vignette.
  • The data.table package and its data.table data structure is know to be fast and able to handle large tables. The dtplyr package provides a (slower) dplyr frontend to data.table.
  • Classical R graphics via e.g. plot, but turn to the lattice package for functionality comparable to ggplot.
